Cathay Financial, Formosa, ManagePay, Petron: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-03-14T20:40:47Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-14/cathay-financial-formosa-managepay-petron-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Cathay Financial Holding Co. (2882 TT):  Taiwan ’s largest
listed financial services company has NT$8.62 billion ($292
million) of exposure to Japan, including NT$7.71 billion in
investments and NT$910 million in loans, the company said in a
statement to Taiwan stock exchange. The shares fell 3.6 percent
to NT$46.05.    Formosa Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT): Taiwan’s only
publicly traded oil refiner said it shut its No. 1 crude
distillation unit yesterday for scheduled maintenance. Crude
processing will fall to between 370,000 and 380,000 barrels a
day in March on average, from about 480,000 barrels in February,
Lin Keh-yen, a company spokesman, said by phone. The stoppage
will last about 40 days, he said. Formosa jumped 6.6 percent to
NT$93.40.    Korea Exchange Bank (004940)  (004940 KS): Korea Exchange Bank will
pay a dividend of 374 billion won ($331 million), or 580 won a
share, the Seoul-based lender said in a regulatory filing. The
shares dropped 0.8 percent to 9,030 won.  ManagePay Systems Bhd. (MPSB MK): Shares of the Malaysian
payment services provider will make its listing debut on the
Kuala Lumpur stock exchange. The company sold shares at 16 sen a
share, according to its prospectus dated Feb. 22.    Petron Corp. (PCOR)  : The larger of the Philippines’ two
oil refiners posted a net income of 7.9 billion pesos ($181
million) in 2010 as sales reached 229.1 billion pesos, it said
in an e-mailed statement. The company didn’t provide comparative
numbers. Petron dropped 1.5 percent to 15 pesos.    San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : The largest Philippine food and
drinks company had net income of 20.1 billion pesos in 2010,
according to a statement. Consolidated revenue rose to 246.1
billion pesos last year and recurring profit in 2010 rose 101
percent, the company said.  San Miguel  dropped 2.1 percent to
160.30 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
